PSA_ORIGINAL = {
  "2": {
    "7": "<p><strong>YHWH amar elai beni atta ani hayom yelidticha</strong> (<em>Yhwh ʾāmar ʾēlay, bĕnî ʾattâ ʾănî hayyôm yĕlídtîkā</em>): 'The LORD said to me: You are my Son; today I have begotten you.' The royal adoption formula of Ps 2:7 was applied to the Davidic king at his enthronement — the king became YHWH's 'son' in a representative capacity (2 Sam 7:14; Ps 89:26-27). The NT applies it to Jesus at three Christological moments: the baptism (Matt 3:17), the transfiguration (2 Pet 1:17), and the resurrection (Acts 13:33; Heb 1:5; 5:5). The resurrection is the decisive 'today' in NT usage: the day of Christ's enthronement at the Father's right hand is the day of divine sonship's full eschatological declaration.</p>"
  },
  "8": {
    "4": "<p><strong>mah enosh ki tizkerenu uben adam ki tipqedenu</strong> (<em>mâ-ʾĕnôš kî-tizqĕrennû ûben-ʾādām kî tipqĕdennû</em>): 'What is man that you are mindful of him, and the son of man that you care for him?' <em>Ben adam</em> (son of man) in Ps 8 is the representative human made lower than the heavenly beings and crowned with glory — a meditation on Gen 1:26-28's dominion mandate. The NT (Heb 2:5-9) applies Ps 8 to Christ as the true human who fulfills the Adamic mandate: 'We do not yet see everything in subjection to him, but we see him who for a little while was made lower than the angels, namely Jesus, crowned with glory and honor because of the suffering of death.' Christ recapitulates and fulfills humanity's Ps 8 vocation.</p>"
  },
  "22": {
    "1": "<p><strong>eli eli lamah azavtani</strong> (<em>ʾēlî ʾēlî lāmāh ʿăzabtānî</em>): 'My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?' The opening of the Passion Psalm in its Hebrew form. The Aramaic at the cross (Mark 15:34: <em>Eloi eloi lema sabachthani</em>) uses the Aramaic form of the Psalm's Hebrew opening, suggesting Jesus was quoting from memory in the vernacular. The Psalm moves from dereliction (vv. 1-21) to proclamation and praise (vv. 22-31) — ending not in abandonment but in universal witness ('all the ends of the earth shall turn to the LORD', v. 27). The early church understood Jesus's citation of the Psalm's opening as invoking the whole Psalm, including its vindication ending.</p>"
  },
  "110": {
    "1": "<p><strong>neum YHWH laadoni shev limini ad ashit oyvecha hadom leraglecha</strong> (<em>nĕʾum Yhwh laʾdōnî, šēb liymînî ʿad-ʾāšît ʾōyĕbêkā hădōm lĕraglêkā</em>): 'The oracle of YHWH to my lord: Sit at my right hand until I make your enemies your footstool.' <em>Neum</em> (oracle of) is the formula for divine speech — the highest possible speech-authority marker in Hebrew prophecy. David writes <em>laadoni</em> (to my lord), creating the theological puzzle Jesus exploits in Matt 22:41-46: how can David's descendant also be David's lord? The Davidic Messiah must be more than a Davidic son; only divine sonship accounts for the double identity. <em>Shev limini</em> (sit at my right hand): enthronement at the supreme position of divine authority — the NT applies this to the resurrection/ascension as Christ's enthronement (Acts 2:34-35; Eph 1:20-21; Heb 1:3).</p>",

    "4": "<p><strong>nishba YHWH velo yinachem atta kohen leolam al divrati malkitsedek</strong> (<em>nišbaʿ Yhwh wĕlōʾ yinnāḥēm ʾattā-kōhēn lĕʿôlām ʿal-diḇrātî malkîṣedeq</em>): 'YHWH has sworn and will not change his mind: You are a priest forever after the manner of Melchizedek.' The divine oath (<em>nishba ... velo yinachem</em>) makes this the most certain OT promise after the Abrahamic oath. <em>Malkitsedek</em> (Melchizedek, king of righteousness): the mysterious priest-king of Gen 14:18-20 who blessed Abraham and received a tithe — without genealogy, without recorded birth or death. Hebrews 7 uses the silence of Scripture about Melchizedek's origins as a typological argument: a priesthood with no recorded beginning or end points to an eternal priesthood.</p>"
  }
}

PSA_CONTEXT = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>The Psalter (150 poems spanning roughly David's reign to the post-exilic period) was the hymnbook of the Second Temple — used in liturgy from the restoration (Ezra-Nehemiah) through the NT period. The Dead Sea Scrolls (1QPs, 4QPsa-r, and 11QPsa) preserve the most psalms of any biblical book among the Qumran community, indicating the Psalter's centrality in Jewish worship. The Psalter is organized into five books (Ps 1-41, 42-72, 73-89, 90-106, 107-150) mirroring the five books of Moses, each ending with a doxology. The arrangement suggests a canonical editorial design: the Psalter tells the story of Israel's covenant relationship with YHWH from Torah-delight (Ps 1) to universal praise (Ps 150).</p>"
  },
  "22": {
    "1": "<p>Psalm 22 is the most cited OT Psalm in the NT Passion narratives. Its historical background (David's persecution?) is unknown — the Psalm presents an archetypal experience of abandonment and vindication. The pattern: intense lament (vv. 1-21) → sudden transition to praise (v. 22) → eschatological proclamation (vv. 27-31: 'all the families of the nations shall worship before you ... posterity shall serve him; it shall be told of the Lord to the coming generation'). The Psalm functions in NT usage not as a prediction of specific details but as the divinely-given interpretive framework for understanding the cross: suffering-unto-vindication, abandonment-unto-universal-proclamation.</p>"
  },
  "41": {
    "1": "<p>Psalm 41 closes Book I of the Psalter (Ps 1-41) and its superscription assigns it to David. 'Blessed is the one who cares for the vulnerable (<em>dal</em>)' — the opening beatitude establishes the covenant principle: YHWH's protection extends to those who protect the weak. The <em>dal</em> (thin, low, weak — often the economically vulnerable without social resources) were a specific object of covenant protection in Israel's law (Deut 15:7-11; Lev 19:9-10). The psalm moves from general principle (vv. 1-3) to personal crisis (vv. 4-9) to petition (vv. 10-11) to doxology (vv. 12-13) — a complete movement from social principle to individual experience.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'The LORD protects and preserves his life; he is regarded as blessed in the land; you will not hand him over to the will of his enemies' — the social blessing network: one who cares for the vulnerable is placed within the same network of covenant protection. The 'blessed in the land' (<em>yeushhar ba'arets</em>) echoes the land-blessing vocabulary of the Abrahamic covenant (Gen 12:2-3) and Deuteronomy's covenant conditions: those who live rightly within the land receive the land's blessing. YHWH's protection of the protector is the reciprocal structure of covenantal justice.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'The LORD supports him on his bed of illness; in his sickness you bring him back to health' — the sick-bed scene shifts the pronominal reference from third person (v. 2) to second person (YHWH directly addressed). Illness in ancient Israel could be socially catastrophic: the sick person lost economic productivity, was sometimes considered ritually unclean (Lev 13-15), and was vulnerable to abandonment by patronage networks. YHWH's support on the sick-bed is the divine patron's direct care when human patrons fall away. The specific image of 'turning the bed' (<em>hafachta miskhavo</em>) may refer to literally turning the sick person to prevent bed-sores — concrete, intimate, physical care.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'As for me, I said, LORD, have mercy on me; heal my soul, for I have sinned against you' — the psalmist enters the narrative as personally sick and personally guilty. The connection between sin and illness was standard in ancient Israelite medicine: sin could produce physical consequences through broken covenant relationship with YHWH. The petition asks for both healing of the body and mercy for the sin: the sick-bed scene is also a scene of moral reckoning. This double petition — heal and forgive — reflects the holistic understanding of human flourishing as both physical and relational.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'My enemies speak wickedly against me: When will he die and his name vanish?' — the 'When will he die' taunt was the social aggression of those who expected the sick man to die and were positioning themselves to benefit from his death and the disappearance of his name (inheritance, legacy). In ancient Israel, a man's 'name' (<em>shem</em>) was his ongoing social identity, preserved through descendants; for the name to 'vanish' meant genealogical extinction — the worst possible fate in a culture where one's name was one's continuity through time. The enemies' desire for the psalmist's extinction is expressed as a desire for total social death.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'When one of them comes to visit me, he mouths empty words while inwardly filing away material against me' — the patron-client protocol required visiting the sick (a social duty); here the visits are exploitative intelligence-gathering. 'Mouths empty words' — the conventional expressions of concern without genuine care. 'Inwardly filing away material' (<em>libbo yiqbots-aven lo</em>, his heart gathers iniquity for himself) — collecting information and evidence to use against the psalmist in legal or social contexts. The visit that should be an act of covenant loyalty becomes an act of betrayal.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'All who hate me whisper together against me; they are plotting disaster for me' — the whispering (<em>yitlachashu</em>) is the covert conspiracy that replaced direct confrontation. In ancient honor-shame culture, open accusation required evidence and courage; covert whispering allowed the destruction of a person's reputation without the accuser becoming accountable. The conspirators 'plot evil' (<em>yachshvu ra'ah</em>) — the word for evil planning used in Joseph's story (Gen 50:20: 'You intended evil against me, but God intended it for good'). The structural echo is deliberate: the righteous sufferer surrounded by plotting enemies.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'They say, Something incurable has seized him; he will never get up from where he is lying' — the medical verdict of the psalmist's enemies: 'a debilitating word (<em>davar beli'ya'al</em>) is poured over him' — literally a 'Belial word' (a word of wickedness/destruction). <em>Beliya'al</em> (often used of worthless/destructive persons) here describes the prognosis: a catastrophic, terminal diagnosis has been attached to the psalmist. 'He will never get up' — the declaration that the sick person will die in bed, removing the enemies' need for any further action. They regard the psalmist as already as good as dead.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Even my closest friend, whom I trusted, who shared my bread, has turned against me' — the table-fellowship violation: the friend who had shared bread (<em>achal lachmi</em>) with the psalmist (the covenant meal that sealed friendship and loyalty) has 'lifted his heel' (<em>higdil aley 'aqev</em>, lifted his heel against me) — a gesture of contempt and betrayal. Sharing bread in the ancient world was a covenant act; to share bread and then betray was to violate the most fundamental social bond. Jesus applies this verse to Judas (John 13:18: 'He who ate my bread has lifted his heel against me'), identifying himself with the righteous sufferer betrayed by a table-companion.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'But you, LORD, have mercy on me and restore me, so that I may give them what they deserve' — the petition for restoration carries an apparently vindictive motivation: restoration in order to retaliate. But in the ancient legal world, 'giving enemies what they deserve' (<em>ashalemah lahem</em>, I will repay them) was the language of covenant justice, not personal revenge. The psalmist is not asking to commit personal violence but to live long enough to see justice served. The phrase echoes Prov 20:22: 'Do not say, I will repay evil; wait for the LORD and he will save you.'</p>",
    "11": "<p>'By this I know that you are pleased with me — my enemy has not triumphed over me' — the covenant sign of divine favor: the enemy's failure to conquer is itself the evidence of YHWH's approval. In the honor-shame framework, YHWH's delight in a person was manifested in their vindication before enemies. The failure of enemies to achieve their goal (the psalmist's death, the extinction of his name) is the visible sign that YHWH is on the psalmist's side. Covenant favor and covenant vindication are empirically connected in Israelite theology.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'As for me, you hold me up in my integrity and place me before your face forever' — the climactic affirmation: integrity (<em>tumi</em>, wholeness/covenant loyalty) as the basis for divine acceptance, and being placed 'before your face' (<em>lefanecha</em>) — in the divine presence — as the ultimate blessing. Temple access was the goal of all the pilgrimage psalms and the highest expression of covenant relationship: to stand before the face of YHWH permanently is the eschatological fulfillment of everything the covenant promised.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Blessed be the LORD, the God of Israel, from everlasting to everlasting. Amen and Amen' — the doxology that closes Book I of the Psalter (Ps 1-41). Each of the five books of the Psalter ends with a doxology: Book I (Ps 41:13), Book II (Ps 72:18-19), Book III (Ps 89:52), Book IV (Ps 106:48), Book V (Ps 150). The doubled 'Amen and Amen' — a liturgical formula of congregation response — indicates that this verse was not part of the original Psalm 41 but was added editorially as the closer of Book I. The Psalter's five-book structure mirrors the Torah's five books.</p>"
  },
  "42": {
    "1": "<p>Psalms 42-43 were almost certainly a single psalm; they share the same refrain (42:5 = 42:11 = 43:5) and Ps 43 lacks its own superscription (unusual in this section of the Psalter). Together they are the opening of Book II (Ps 42-72), the 'Elohistic Psalter' where the divine name YHWH is systematically replaced with <em>Elohim</em> — a different editorial practice from Book I. The 'Sons of Korah' (<em>bene qorach</em>) were a guild of temple singers and gatekeepers (1 Chr 9:17-19; 26:1-19); the Korah psalms (42-49, 84, 85, 87, 88) likely originated in their liturgical tradition. 'As a deer longs for flowing streams' — the deer panting for water in a dry wadi is the visceral image of covenant thirst.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'My soul thirsts for God, for the living God. When will I come and stand in God's presence?' — the language of temple pilgrimage and desire for the divine presence. 'The living God' (<em>el chay</em>) as opposed to the dead gods of the nations — the one who is actually present and active. 'When will I come and appear before God' (<em>eraeh pene Elohim</em>?) — the phrasing echoes the pilgrimage commandment of Exod 34:23-24: 'Three times a year all your males shall appear before the Lord GOD.' The psalmist is apparently cut off from the temple and longs for the annual festival appearances before YHWH.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'My tears have been my food day and night, while people keep saying to me all day long, Where is your God?' — 'Where is your God?' (<em>ayeh Elohecha</em>) was the taunt of those who interpreted the psalmist's evident suffering as evidence of divine absence or abandonment (cf. Ps 79:10; Joel 2:17; Mic 7:10). If YHWH was truly the psalmist's God and patron, why was the psalmist suffering? The taunt exploited the ANE principle that suffering = divine disfavor. Tears as 'food' — the metaphor inverts the table: instead of food that sustains, grief consumes the person.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'These things I remember as I pour out my soul: how I used to walk with the crowd, leading them in procession to the house of God, with shouts of joy and thanksgiving among the festive throng' — the memory of the temple procession is both comfort and source of renewed grief. The psalmist had participated in and led (<em>edadem</em>, I was walking as leader) the pilgrimage processions to Jerusalem's temple — a public, joyful, communal event. Now separated from these, the memory intensifies the longing. The festive shouts and thanksgiving (<em>qol rinnah vetodah</em>) characterize the communal worship that the psalmist desperately misses.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Why are you downcast, O my soul? Why so disturbed within me? Put your hope in God, for I will yet praise him, my Savior and my God' — the refrain that appears in 42:5, 42:11, and 43:5 is the theological center of the combined psalm. The psalmist dialogues with his own soul (<em>nephesh</em>): addressing himself rather than YHWH, asking why the interior life has collapsed into despair. The self-address is therapeutic and theological: the soul's downcast state is questioned, not accepted. The affirmation 'I will yet praise him' (<em>ki od odenu</em>) is a future-oriented hope that refuses to interpret present circumstances as permanent.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'My soul is cast down within me; therefore I remember you from the land of the Jordan, the heights of Hermon, from Mount Mizar' — the geographical markers place the psalmist in the far north of Israel: the Jordan headwaters, Mount Hermon (the highest peak in the region, on the border of modern Lebanon/Syria), and the unidentified 'little mountain' (<em>har-Mizar</em>). From this great distance from Jerusalem, the psalmist remembers (<em>ezkarcha</em>) YHWH — making memory of the covenant relationship substitute for physical presence at the temple. Distance from the sanctuary intensifies rather than destroys the covenantal connection.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Deep calls to deep at the roar of your waterfalls; all your waves and breakers have rolled over me' — the overwhelming waters image drawn from the geography of the Jordan headwaters near Hermon, where multiple streams converge with dramatic force. The 'deep calling to deep' (<em>tehom-el-tehom qore'</em>) uses the cosmic water language of Gen 1:2 (<em>tehom</em>, the primordial deep): the waters are not merely natural but cosmically threatening. YHWH's own 'waves and breakers' (<em>mishbarecha</em>) have swept over the psalmist — the affliction is experienced as coming from YHWH himself, not merely human enemies.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'By day the LORD directs his steadfast love, and at night his song is with me, a prayer to the God of my life' — the day/night merism of continuous divine provision: <em>hesed</em> (covenant love/faithfulness) by day; his song (<em>shiro</em>, a song directed to me) by night. Night in ancient Israel was the time of greatest vulnerability (no light, predators active, enemies able to move unseen); YHWH's song accompanying the psalmist through the night is the covenant presence sustaining through maximum danger. 'God of my life' (<em>el chayyai</em>) — YHWH as the source and sustainer of the psalmist's vitality.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'I say to God my rock, Why have you forgotten me? Why do I go about mourning under the oppression of the enemy?' — 'my rock' (<em>sal'i</em>, my cliff/crag) is the image of the massive, stable stone fortress that shelters those who take refuge in it (cf. Ps 18:2; 31:3). The paradox: YHWH is named as the rock, yet the psalmist experiences 'forgetting' (<em>shechachtani</em>) — the divine patron apparently inactive in the crisis. The question 'Why have you forgotten me?' is the ancient form of the theodicy question: how can the covenant patron be absent when the client is in distress?</p>",
    "10": "<p>'As if a sword were cutting through my bones, my enemies taunt me, saying to me all day, Where is your God?' — the taunt 'Where is your God?' returns (cf. v. 3), but here the psalmist describes it as a physical sensation: like the shattering of bones. In the honor-shame world, public taunt was not merely emotional — it was social violence. The enemies' repeated questioning of YHWH's existence or care was an attack on the psalmist's covenantal identity: to be a person whose God is absent is to be a person without standing.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Why are you downcast, O my soul? Why are you in turmoil within me? Put your hope in God; for I will yet praise him, my Savior and my God' — the second occurrence of the refrain (the third appears in 43:5). The refrain's repetition creates the structure of the combined psalm: each strophe of lament is answered by the same affirmation of future praise. This is not denial of present reality but prophetic declaration against it: despite all evidence (tears, exile, oppression, divine silence), the covenant God will be praised. The soul that is tutored by this refrain practices covenant trust in the face of its collapse.</p>"
  },
  "43": {
    "1": "<p>'Vindicate me, O God, and plead my cause against an ungodly nation; from the deceitful and unjust man deliver me' — the legal petition that opens Ps 43 (the second half of the combined Ps 42-43 psalm). 'Vindicate me' (<em>shaphteni</em>, judge me, render a verdict for me) — the appeal for divine adjudication in a legal dispute. The psalmist is surrounded by an 'ungodly nation' (<em>goy lo-chasid</em>, a people without covenant loyalty) — suggesting the exile or dispersion context where the psalmist is surrounded by non-Israelites whose court systems do not recognize YHWH's authority. The appeal bypasses human courts to the divine judge.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'For you are the God who is my stronghold; why have you rejected me? Why do I go about mourning under the oppression of the enemy?' — the same paradox as 42:9: YHWH named as 'God of my stronghold' (<em>el ma'uzi</em>, the God of my refuge/fortress) while experiencing what feels like divine rejection (<em>zemachtani</em>, you have cast me off). The paradox is not resolved by denying either side: the psalmist holds both the covenant identity of YHWH (fortress) and the experiential reality (rejection) simultaneously, pressing both into the petition. The mourning walk under enemy oppression is the physical enactment of covenant grief.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Send out your light and your truth; let them lead me, let them bring me to your holy mountain and to your dwelling' — light (<em>orcha</em>) and truth/faithfulness (<em>amitecha</em>) are personified as divine messengers sent to escort the psalmist back to the temple. The 'holy mountain' (<em>har qodshecha</em>) is Zion; the 'dwelling' (<em>mishkanotecha</em>, your tents/tabernacles) is the sanctuary complex. The request to be led back to the temple is both geographical (physical return from exile or exile-like distance) and spiritual: to be brought back into the place of covenant encounter. Light and truth are the qualities of divine guidance that make the path findable.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Then I will approach the altar of God, to God who is my greatest joy, and I will praise you with the lyre, O God, my God' — the <em>todah</em> (thanksgiving) vow: if YHWH brings the psalmist back to the sanctuary, worship and praise will follow. 'My greatest joy' (<em>simchat gili</em>, the joy of my rejoicing) — the temple and its worship as the psalmist's supreme source of delight, contrasted with all other pleasures. The lyre (<em>kinor</em>) was the instrument of the temple singers (1 Chr 15:16; 25:1-6; Ps 33:2; 71:22). The anticipated praise is not merely emotional but liturgical and performative.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Why are you downcast, O my soul? Why are you in turmoil within me? Put your hope in God; for I will yet praise him, my Savior and my God' — the third and final occurrence of the combined psalm's refrain. The refrain here comes not after additional lament but as the conclusion of the petition (Ps 43:1-4): having cried out, having asked for divine guidance, having vowed the return to the altar, the soul now addresses itself with the settled conviction of the first two refrains. The three-fold repetition creates a rhetorical and liturgical completion: the petition has been made, the vow declared, and the soul's answer to its own despair is the covenant affirmation.</p>"
  },
  "44": {
    "1": "<p>Psalm 44 is one of the great national laments of the OT — alongside Ps 74, 79, 80, 89 — arising from a military defeat that the psalmist cannot explain theologically. 'O God, we have heard with our own ears; our ancestors have told us what you did in their days, in the days of old' — the prayer opens with the recitation of covenant history. 'Our ancestors told us' (<em>avotenu siperu lanu</em>) — the transmission chain of Deut 6:20-25: the Exodus generation's testimony passed to their children, who passed it to the next generation. The recitation of saving history is the standard opening move of Israel's communal lament: first establish the covenant basis, then press YHWH with the current contradiction.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'With your own hand you drove out the nations and planted our ancestors; you crushed the peoples and expelled them' — the Conquest as YHWH's own military act: the nations were driven out not by Israel's military prowess but by divine power. 'Planted our ancestors' (<em>tita'em</em>, you planted them like a plant) — the agricultural metaphor for YHWH establishing Israel in the land (cf. Exod 15:17: 'You will bring them in and plant them on the mountain of your own possession'). The narrative established YHWH's absolute capability in the past as the grounds for the present complaint about inaction.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'For they did not win the land by their own sword, and their own arm did not deliver them; it was your right hand and your arm and the light of your face, for you loved them' — the explicit theological claim about the Conquest: Israel did not accomplish it by military means. The 'right hand' (<em>yemimecha</em>), 'arm' (<em>zero'echa</em>), and 'light of your face' (<em>or panecha</em>) are divine warrior terminology: YHWH personally fought for Israel in the Conquest (Josh 23:3-5). 'Because you loved them' (<em>ki retsitam</em>, because you were favorable to them) — the Conquest as expression of covenant love, not military competence.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'You are my King, O God; decree victories for Jacob' — the singular pronoun ('my King') amidst the communal psalm may represent the king speaking on behalf of the nation, or a transition to individual petition within the communal context. 'Decree victories for Jacob' (<em>tsavveh yeshu'ot ya'aqov</em>) — the sovereign issuing a royal decree of salvation: YHWH as the cosmic king whose word accomplishes what it commands (cf. Isa 45:23: 'I have sworn by myself, the word has gone out in righteousness and shall not return').</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Through you we push back our enemies; in your name we trample those who rise against us' — the covenant-warfare theology: Israel's military success comes 'through' (<em>becha</em>) YHWH and 'in your name' (<em>bishimcha</em>). The divine name was not magic but the invocation of the divine patron's power and commitment to the covenant (cf. Deut 20:1-4: the command not to fear the enemy because YHWH goes with the army). This verse (alongside v. 6) provides the theological contrast that makes the lament of vv. 9-16 so devastating: if military success is always 'through YHWH,' military failure is insoluble.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'For I do not trust in my bow, and my sword cannot bring me victory' — the explicit rejection of military self-reliance. The bow and sword (<em>kashti</em>, <em>charbi</em>) were the primary weapons of ancient Israelite warriors; the psalmist declares that these instruments are not the source of victory. This is the theological complement to the historical recital of vv. 1-3: just as the ancestors did not win the land by military means, the present generation does not trust in military means. The foundation is established for the lament: if it's not our military failure, why have we been defeated?</p>",
    "7": "<p>'But you have saved us from our enemies and disgraced those who hate us' — past tense: prior experience of divine military protection. The contrast between this affirmed past experience and the present reality of defeat (v. 9 onwards) is the heart of the lament. YHWH has demonstrably saved in the past; his failure to save in the present is inexplicable and demands theological resolution.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'In God we have boasted all day long, and we will praise your name forever. Selah' — public testimony as covenant act: the community has declared YHWH's saving power publicly (boasted = <em>hillalnu</em>, we have praised/boasted of). The '<em>Selah</em>' pause marks the transition from the confident recital of past faithfulness to the devastating 'But' of v. 9. The structural contrast is deliberate: praise/boast → but you have rejected us. The 'Selah' is the musical and rhetorical hinge of the entire psalm.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'But you have cast us off and brought us to disgrace, and have not gone out with our armies' — the central accusation: YHWH has 'cast off' (<em>zaneachta</em>, rejected, thrust away) and 'disgraced' (<em>techfir</em>) his people. Most critically: 'you have not gone out with our armies' — YHWH has not accompanied the Israelite army to battle. The divine warrior was expected to go before his people in warfare (Num 10:33-36; Josh 6:2-5; 2 Sam 5:22-25). YHWH's absence from the battlefield was the theological catastrophe that military defeat merely expressed. The defeat was a symptom; the absence was the crisis.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'You made us retreat before the enemy, and our enemies plundered us' — the reversal of the Conquest narrative: instead of Israel driving out the nations (v. 2), Israel is driven back. The plundering (<em>vayyishsasu</em>) of Israel by its enemies is the inversion of the covenant blessing — Deut 28:29 describes plundering as one of the covenant curses for disobedience. But the psalmist has not confessed disobedience (cf. vv. 17-21: 'We have not forgotten you, and we have not been unfaithful to your covenant') — making the plundering theologically unaccountable.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'You handed us over like sheep for slaughter and scattered us among the nations' — the sheep-for-slaughter image: Israel as a passive flock delivered to butchers. 'Scattered among the nations' (<em>tizrem bagoyim</em>) — the Diaspora image that the prophets used for divine judgment (Ezek 11:16; Zech 7:14; Deut 4:27: 'The LORD will scatter you among the peoples'). The scattering among nations is the canonical curse for covenant violation, yet the psalmist will claim (v. 17) that no such violation has occurred. The gap between deserved and experienced punishment is the psalm's theological engine.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'You sold your people for a pittance and made no profit from the sale' — the striking commercial metaphor: YHWH 'selling' (<em>timkor</em>) his people not even for a profitable price but at a loss. This is simultaneously an accusation and an absurdity: why would YHWH sell his people without gain? The logic presses on YHWH's own interest: the transaction is not even economically rational. Isa 52:3 uses the same language: 'You were sold for nothing, and without money you will be redeemed' — the free redemption is the inversion of the free sale.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'You have made us the object of mockery to our neighbors, a laughingstock and a source of scorn to those around us' — the shame of national defeat before neighboring nations. In the honor-shame world, national defeat was divine dishonor: the nations around Israel interpreted Israel's God as weak or absent. The 'laughingstock' (<em>kelimmah</em>, shame/dishonor) and 'scorn' (<em>laag</em>, mockery) were the social consequences of military failure — Israel's defeat was read as YHWH's defeat. The nations' mockery was not merely offensive to Israel but to YHWH himself, which is the basis for the prayer in Ps 79:10 and Ezek 36:22: act for your name's sake among the nations.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'You have made us a byword among the nations, a wagging of heads among the peoples' — 'a byword' (<em>mashal</em>, a proverb/saying) — Israel has become a cautionary example cited in the speech of other nations (cf. Deut 28:37: 'you will become an object of horror and ridicule and scorn among all the nations'). The 'wagging of heads' (<em>menod-rosh bagoyim</em>) is the head-shaking gesture of contempt seen in Ps 22:7; Lam 2:15. To become the object of this gesture from surrounding nations was the maximum dishonor: no longer just a failing people but the definition of failure itself.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'All day long my disgrace is before me, and shame has covered my face' — the internalized shame: not just external mockery but the psalmist's own consciousness of dishonor. 'Shame has covered my face' (<em>kissetah bosheth panay</em>) — the face (the primary site of honor and shame in ancient culture) has been obscured by shame. The phrase 'all day long' (<em>kol-hayyom</em>) indicates that this is not a momentary embarrassment but a persistent state — the shame has become chronic, a defining condition of daily existence.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'On account of the taunting voice of the one who reviles and blasphemes, because of the enemy who seeks revenge' — the 'reviling' (<em>mecharef</em>) and 'blaspheming' (<em>megaddef</em>) are related to the same honor-dishonor system: the enemy who mocks Israel's God is committing blasphemy (dishonoring the divine name) and reviling (attacking Israel's honor as YHWH's people). The enemy's revenge-seeking motive suggests a specific historical conflict rather than general hostility.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'All this has come upon us, yet we have not forgotten you, and we have not been unfaithful to your covenant' — the pivotal theological claim that sets Ps 44 apart from psalms of penitential lament (Ps 6, 32, 38, 51). Here the community explicitly denies covenant violation: the standard Deuteronomic explanation (defeat = covenant violation) is rejected. This is the psalm of the 'innocent sufferer' at the national level — analogous to Job's position at the individual level. The denial of guilt makes the suffering genuinely inexplicable and the theodicy question genuinely pressing.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Our heart has not turned away, and our steps have not strayed from your path' — the reinforcement of the innocence claim. 'Heart' (<em>lev</em>) and 'steps' (<em>ashurennu</em>) cover interior and exterior: neither inner allegiance nor outward conduct has deviated from the covenant path. This double claim (inward + outward fidelity) echoes the entrance liturgy criteria of Ps 24:3-4 (clean hands + pure heart). The community is not being falsely modest — the claim is made before the God who knows the hidden things of the heart (v. 21).</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Yet you have crushed us in the haunt of jackals and covered us with the shadow of death' — the desert ruins as the scene of divine punishment. 'Haunt of jackals' (<em>meqom tannin</em>, place of sea-monsters/jackals) — wild, desolate places associated with divine judgment and abandonment (cf. Isa 34:13; Jer 9:11 where jackals howl in the ruins of devastated cities). 'Shadow of death' (<em>tsalmevet</em> — the same word as Ps 23:4 in most traditions) — the profound darkness of near-death. The community has been placed in the landscape of divine curse without having committed the violations that should produce that curse.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'If we had forgotten the name of our God or spread our hands in prayer toward a foreign god' — the conditional structure (vv. 20-21) is a formal oath of innocence before the divine court. The two prohibited acts: (1) forgetting the divine name (<em>shem Elohenu</em>) = abandoning YHWH's covenantal identity; (2) spreading hands to a foreign god — the gesture of prayer toward an idol. Both constitute idolatry in different forms: cognitive (forgetting) and ritual (gesturing toward). The condition sets up the appeal to divine omniscience in v. 21.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Would God not discover this? For he knows the hidden things of the heart' — the appeal to divine omniscience as the guarantor of the innocence oath. YHWH 'knows the hidden things of the heart' (<em>hu yode'a ta'alumot lev</em>) — he cannot be deceived by external righteousness concealing interior idolatry. The same omniscience that would have detected the violation (if it existed) now certifies that it does not exist. The community's confidence in pleading innocent before the omniscient God is itself evidence of their sincerity: they know they cannot deceive him.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Yet for your sake we face death all day long; we are counted as sheep destined for slaughter' — one of the most significant verses in the psalm: the suffering is 'for your sake' (<em>alecha</em>). The community's suffering is not punishment for their sin but something connected to their identity as YHWH's people in a hostile world. Paul cites this verse in Rom 8:36, embedding it in the argument that neither persecution nor suffering nor death can separate believers from the love of God in Christ: those who belong to YHWH face death in this age as the consistent experience of covenant identity.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'Wake up! Why are you sleeping, O Lord? Rise up! Do not reject us forever!' — the most audacious address in the Psalter: accusing YHWH of sleeping (<em>quma al-tishkach</em>, arise, do not forget!). YHWH sleeping was an unthinkable claim — Ps 121:3-4 explicitly denies it: 'He who watches over you will not slumber; indeed, he who watches over Israel will neither slumber nor sleep.' The rhetorical hyperbole functions not as a theological claim but as a desperate dramatic appeal: YHWH's inaction so resembles sleep that the psalmist uses the language of waking to demand divine attention. The Elijah-and-Baal parallel (1 Kgs 18:27: 'Maybe he is sleeping') uses the same logic satirically.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'Why do you hide your face? Why do you ignore our affliction and our oppression?' — divine face-hiding (<em>taster panecha</em>) returns (cf. Ps 27:9; 30:7; Isa 8:17; 54:8): the withdrawal of divine presence and covenant attention. The parallel questions 'Why hide?' and 'Why ignore?' press YHWH on both his presence (face hidden) and his attentiveness (forgetting affliction). The community's affliction (<em>oniyenu</em>) and oppression (<em>lachatsenu</em>) are facts on the ground demanding divine response; YHWH's apparent indifference to them is the crisis the psalm names.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'For our soul is brought down to the dust; our body clings to the ground' — extreme physical and social prostration: the community is at ground level, unable to rise. The 'dust' (<em>aphar</em>) is the threshold of death (Gen 3:19; Ps 22:15, 29); 'clings to the ground' (<em>davqah la'arets bitnenu</em>, our belly clings to the earth) is the posture of the defeated and humiliated, face-down in the dirt before the conqueror. The image is simultaneously military (defeated soldiers prostrated before the victor) and existential (the community at the edge of extinction).</p>",
    "26": "<p>'Rise up and help us! Deliver us for the sake of your steadfast love (<em>hesed</em>)!' — the final petition grounds the appeal not in Israel's merit (the community has disclaimed that basis throughout the psalm) but in YHWH's own <em>hesed</em> — the committed covenant love that is part of YHWH's character regardless of circumstances. The appeal to <em>hesed</em> is the most foundational possible ground: it asks YHWH to act according to who he is, not according to what Israel deserves. The Psalter consistently uses <em>hesed</em> as the last and most unassailable basis for petition.</p>"
  },
  "45": {
    "1": "<p>Psalm 45 is the only psalm that is explicitly a wedding song — a composition for a royal marriage. Its superscription calls it <em>shir yedidot</em> ('song of loves/beloved ones') and attributes it to the Sons of Korah for the choirmaster. 'My heart is overflowing with a beautiful theme; I compose my poem for the king' — the psalmist describes his own composition process: the heart overflows (<em>rachash libby davar tov</em>, my heart stirs/bubbles up with a good word) like a spring. The explicit artistic self-description ('my tongue is like the pen of a skilled scribe') is rare in the Psalter and marks this as a piece of conscious literary craft. Hebrews 1:8-9 applies this psalm to Christ.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'You are more handsome than any other man; grace is poured into your lips; therefore God has blessed you forever' — royal praise poetry of the king's physical beauty was a genre in ANE court literature (Egyptian and Mesopotamian royal encomia regularly praised the king's divine appearance). 'Grace is poured into your lips' (<em>hutsak chen bisfatecha</em>) — the king's speech is itself a gift: his words carry persuasive power and covenant authority. 'God has blessed you forever' — the eternal blessing connects the royal person to the Davidic covenant promise (2 Sam 7:13-16: 'I will establish your kingdom forever').</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Strap your sword on your thigh, O champion (<em>gibbor</em>), in your glory and splendor' — the transition to the king's military identity. <em>Gibbor</em> (warrior/hero/mighty man) was a key epithet for the ideal king and, in messianic texts, for the coming ruler (Isa 9:6: 'Wonderful Counselor, Mighty God (<em>el gibbor</em>), Everlasting Father, Prince of Peace'). The sword on the thigh was the standard position for a warrior ready for battle. The call to ride forth in 'glory and splendor' (<em>hod vehadar</em>) uses the terminology of divine royalty (cf. Ps 96:6: 'Splendor and majesty are before him').</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Ride out victoriously in your splendor for the sake of truth, humility, and righteousness; let your right hand display awesome deeds' — the king's military campaign is not mere conquest but covenant justice: he rides 'for the sake of truth (<em>emet</em>), humility (<em>anava</em>), and righteousness (<em>tsedek</em>).' These three qualities are the same attributes demanded of the covenant-faithful Israelite in Micah 6:8 ('do justice, love kindness, walk humbly'). The ideal king's military power is morally ordered: his right hand does 'awesome deeds' (<em>nora'ot</em>) in the service of covenant values, not mere imperial ambition.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Your arrows are sharp, bringing peoples down beneath you; they pierce into the hearts of the king's enemies' — the arrow imagery of divine-warrior literature: the king as archer whose arrows pierce hearts (cf. Ps 7:13; Lam 3:12-13; Isa 49:2: the Servant's mouth 'like a sharp sword' and himself 'like a polished arrow'). The 'peoples' (<em>ammim</em>) falling beneath the royal warrior evokes the enthronement Psalms (Ps 47:3: 'He subdues peoples under us') and the Abrahamic promise of universal blessing/dominion.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Your throne, O God, is forever and ever; the scepter of your kingdom is a righteous scepter' — one of the most theologically significant lines in the Psalter: the king is addressed as 'God' (<em>Elohim</em>). The interpretation is debated: is this hyperbolic address to the human king (as in Egyptian court language where the pharaoh was called divine)? Or is it a genuine divine predication? Hebrews 1:8-9 takes it as the latter, applying the verse directly to the Son: 'Your throne, O God, is forever and ever.' The 'righteous scepter' is the instrument of the king's just rule — the scepter as symbol of royal judicial authority.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'You have loved righteousness and hated wickedness; therefore God, your God, has anointed you with the oil of gladness beyond your companions' — the moral foundation of the royal anointing: the king's love of righteousness and hatred of wickedness is the basis of the divine choice. The 'oil of gladness' (<em>shemen sason</em>) is the anointing oil applied to kings at coronation (1 Sam 10:1; 16:13; 1 Kgs 1:39) and to the high priest (Lev 21:10), but here expressed as oil of joy — covenant celebration. 'Beyond your companions' (<em>mechavereicha</em>) — the king is set apart from all peers by this divine anointing.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'All your robes are fragrant with myrrh, aloes, and cassia; from ivory palaces the music of strings has made you glad' — myrrh, aloes, and cassia were the costliest imported perfumes in the ancient Near East, used in temple worship (Exod 30:23-25: the anointing oil formula uses myrrh and cassia) and in royal contexts. The 'ivory palaces' (<em>minei-shen</em>) recall Solomon's ivory throne (1 Kgs 10:18) and Ahab's 'ivory house' condemned by Amos (Amos 3:15; 6:4): the wealth of the royal court encoded in architecture. The sensory richness (fragrance + music) paints the wedding scene with maximum luxuriance.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Daughters of kings are among your ladies of honor; at your right hand stands the queen arrayed in gold of Ophir' — the position of the queen 'at your right hand' is the position of the honored advocate and royal partner (cf. 1 Kgs 2:19: Bathsheba's seat at Solomon's right hand). 'Gold of Ophir' was the most prized gold in the ancient world (1 Kgs 9:28; 10:11; Job 28:16) — its appearance here signals maximum royal wealth. The daughters of foreign kings ('ladies of honor') represent the political dimension of royal marriage: diplomatic alliances sealed through marriage.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Listen, daughter, and pay attention; lean in with your ear: forget your own people and your father's house' — the Psalm's address now turns to the queen/bride. The command to 'forget' her people and father's house echoes the Abrahamic call (Gen 12:1: 'Leave your country, your people, and your father's household') and anticipates the marriage covenant: the bride enters a new loyalty structure. The bride's new identity is defined by her relationship to the king, not her family of origin. The NT application (Eph 5:25-32: the church as bride of Christ) picks up this leaving-and-cleaving pattern.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Then the king will desire your beauty; because he is your lord, bow down to him' — the instruction to submit to the king as lord (<em>adon</em>) is the covenant submission of the wife to the husband in Israelite marriage law (cf. Gen 18:12: Sarah calls Abraham 'lord'; 1 Pet 3:5-6: Sarah's submission as the pattern for holy wives). The king's desire for the bride's beauty (<em>yit'av hamelech yofyech</em>) reciprocates: submission is within a relationship of mutual desire and covenant honor.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'The daughter of Tyre comes bearing a gift; the wealthy among the nations will seek your favor' — Tyre was the preeminent trading city of the ancient Mediterranean world (cf. Ezek 27-28's extended lament over Tyre; Isa 23). The 'daughter of Tyre' bearing a gift to the wedding represents the wealth of international commerce flowing toward the royal court. The gathering of 'wealthy of the nations' (<em>ashirei am</em>) anticipates the eschatological vision of Ps 22:27-29 and Isa 60:5-7 where the nations' wealth flows to Zion.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'The king's daughter is altogether beautiful within; her garment is interwoven with gold' — 'altogether beautiful within' (<em>kol-kevudah bat-melech penimah</em>, all the glory of the king's daughter is inward) — the queen's beauty is described as interior (<em>penimah</em>, within) before exterior. This sequence (interior then exterior) reflects the covenant principle that inner character precedes outward display. The gold-interwoven garments are the exterior confirmation of the interior glory.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'In embroidered garments she will be led to the king; the maidens, her companions, will follow her and will be brought to you' — the wedding procession: the bride led formally to the king's presence, attended by her companions (bridesmaids). The formal leading (<em>tuval lamelech</em>, she will be brought to the king) uses the same ceremonial language as bringing offerings to the temple — the approach to the king has sacral overtones. The attendant maidens form the cortège that dignifies and witnesses the procession.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'With joy and celebration they will be led in; they will enter the king's palace' — the joy (<em>rinnah vesimchah</em>) characterizes the wedding procession's entrance into the palace. The 'palace' (<em>hekal</em>) is the same word as 'temple' — the royal palace and the divine sanctuary share the same architectural and semantic space in ancient Israelite thinking. The entrance of the bride to the king's palace has symbolic depth: the covenant union of ruler and bride in the royal sanctuary.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'In place of your ancestors will be your sons; you will appoint them as princes throughout all the earth' — the dynastic promise: the sons of this royal marriage will become princes. The language echoes the Davidic covenant promise (2 Sam 7:12-13: 'I will raise up your offspring after you ... I will establish his kingdom') and extends it to universal scope: 'princes throughout all the earth' (<em>lesharim bechol-ha'arets</em>). The marriage's fruit is a royal lineage that extends across the known world.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'I will cause your name to be remembered in all generations; therefore the peoples will praise you forever and ever' — the psalmist's own vow and task: to make the king's name perpetually remembered. 'Name remembered' (<em>azkir shemcha</em>) is the covenant memory function: the act of keeping the king's name in circulation through literature, liturgy, and transmission. This verse closes the psalm with the psalmist's own commission: the wedding song is itself an act of covenant memory-making, extending the king's name beyond the moment of the wedding into all future generations.</p>"
  },
  "46": {
    "1": "<p>Psalm 46 is among the most influential psalms in Christian history: Martin Luther composed <em>Ein feste Burg ist unser Gott</em> (A Mighty Fortress Is Our God, 1529) based on it. The psalm's opening 'God is our refuge and strength, a help always present in trouble' became Luther's theological response to the Reformation's crisis. The 'Sons of Korah' superscription places it in the levitical singer tradition. The psalm describes cosmic dissolution and political chaos (vv. 2-3, 6) and responds with the Zion theology of YHWH's permanent presence in the city (vv. 4-5). 'Our refuge (<em>machase</em>) and strength (<em>oz</em>)' — two complementary images of YHWH's protective power: shelter and force.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Therefore we will not fear, even if the earth gives way, even if the mountains topple into the heart of the sea' — the cosmic dissolution scenario: the reversal of creation order. The earth 'giving way' (<em>bemut arets</em>, when the earth changes/is removed) and mountains falling into the sea are the images of the uncreation of the world — what happens when the chaotic waters overcome the boundaries established at creation. Ancient Near Eastern creation myths described the primordial chaos as the waters (Babylonian <em>Tiamat</em>) overcome by the divine warrior. Ps 46 uses this imagery to say: even if the entire creation unravels, YHWH's people will not fear. The spatial imagery of the cosmos itself collapsing is the maximally extreme case.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Though the waters roar and churn, though the mountains quake at the surging sea. Selah' — the continuation of the cosmic chaos image: roaring waters (<em>yehemu meimav</em>), mountains 'trembling' (<em>yirashun harim</em>) at the sea's pride/arrogance (<em>bigavato</em>). The Selah musical/liturgical pause here follows the maximally threatening image — the congregation pauses to take in the picture of cosmic dissolution before hearing the counter-image of the divine city's security (v. 4). The dramatic function of Selah as rhetorical pause is clear in this psalm's structure.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'There is a river whose streams bring joy to the city of God, the sacred dwelling of the Most High' — the contrast: amid cosmic dissolution (vv. 2-3), a river (<em>nahar</em>) flows peacefully through the city of God. This river is not geographical (Jerusalem has no river; the nearest body of water is the Gihon spring and the Kidron valley). It is the river of Eden (Gen 2:10: the river watering the garden from which four branches flow) and anticipates the eschatological river of Rev 22:1-2 ('the river of the water of life, bright as crystal, flowing from the throne of God and of the Lamb'). The river signals that the city of God is the new Eden.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'God is within her; she will not be shaken; God will help her when morning breaks' — 'God is within her' (<em>Elohim bekerebah</em>, God is in her midst) is the Zion theology's central claim: the divine presence (<em>kavod</em>) dwelling in the temple makes the city itself uniquely stable. The formula echoes Moses's prayer in Exod 33:15-16: 'If your Presence does not go with us, do not send us up from here.' Without the divine presence, the city is just a city; with it, it cannot be shaken. 'When morning breaks' (<em>liphnot boqer</em>) — the morning was the expected time of divine action in battle and the standard time of divine help in the Psalter (Ps 30:5; 59:16; 90:14).</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Nations raged and kingdoms shook; he lifted his voice, and the earth dissolved' — the political chaos parallel to the cosmic chaos of vv. 2-3: raging nations and shaking kingdoms are the human-historical version of the dissolving earth and plunging mountains. But where the cosmic dissolution requires the river of v. 4 to calm, the political dissolution is resolved by a single act: YHWH lifting his voice (<em>natan beqolo</em>, gives his voice = speaks/thunders). The divine word of power dissolves the kingdoms that raged — the cosmic rebuke of Ps 18:15 and Isa 66:6. The contrast between the nations' rage and YHWH's single utterance establishes the complete disproportion between created power and divine authority.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'The LORD of Armies (<em>Yhwh Tseva'ot</em>) is with us; the God of Jacob is our fortress. Selah' — the first of two identical refrains (also v. 11; a third refrain may have been present before v. 1 in some reconstructions). <em>Yhwh Tseva'ot</em> (LORD of Hosts/Armies) — the divine commander of heavenly and earthly armies (cf. Ps 24:10). 'The God of Jacob' (<em>Elohei ya'aqov</em>) — the covenant God of the patriarchs who chose the specific, particular people of Israel. The two divine titles work together: cosmic commander + covenant patriarchal God. 'Fortress' (<em>misgav</em>, high-place/stronghold) is the third protection image in the psalm after 'refuge' and 'strength' (v. 1).</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Come and see what the LORD has done, what desolations he has brought upon the earth' — the invitation to observe YHWH's acts in history. 'Desolations' (<em>shammot</em>, wastes/ruins) that YHWH has caused are not random destruction but the ruins left by his defeat of the raging nations (v. 6). The command 'come and see' (<em>lechu chazu</em>) is the prophetic call to empirical observation of YHWH's historical interventions: the ruins are evidence that the divine warrior has been active. Ps 66:5 uses the same call: 'Come and see what God has done.'</p>",
    "9": "<p>'He puts an end to wars across the whole earth; he breaks bows and cuts spears apart; he burns the war chariots' — the eschatological disarmament: YHWH ending wars and destroying weapons throughout the earth. The broken bow, cut spear, and burned chariot are the three principal weapons of ancient Near Eastern warfare — covering long-range (bow), close-range (spear), and mobile (chariot) military capacity. This verse is the Psalmic parallel to Isa 2:4 ('They will beat their swords into plowshares') and Mic 4:3 — the prophetic vision of universal peace through divine disarmament. The weapons are not laid down voluntarily but destroyed by YHWH.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Be still, and know that I am God; I will be exalted among the nations; I will be exalted throughout the earth' — 'Be still' (<em>harpu</em>) is not primarily a devotional call to quiet prayer but a command in the military context: 'stop fighting, stand down, cease resistance.' The full meaning: 'Let your hands drop (stop fighting) and know that I am God.' YHWH's word to the raging nations is the command to acknowledge his sovereignty. 'I will be exalted among the nations' (<em>arum bagoyim</em>) — the eschatological outcome of all history: universal recognition of divine sovereignty. This verse functions as YHWH's own speech within the Psalm.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'The LORD of Armies is with us; the God of Jacob is our fortress. Selah' — the closing refrain (identical to v. 7) brackets the central content (vv. 8-10: YHWH's historical desolations and eschatological disarmament) with the covenant community's confession. The double declaration — YHWH with us, YHWH our fortress — is the theological anchor against which both cosmic dissolution (vv. 2-3) and political chaos (v. 6) are measured and found wanting. The final Selah closes the psalm with space for the confession to resonate.</p>"
  },
  "47": {
    "1": "<p>Psalm 47 is an enthronement psalm — a psalm celebrating YHWH's kingship over all nations. The enthronement psalms (Ps 47, 93, 96-99) were likely used in the autumn festival (Sukkot/Tabernacles) and in Jewish tradition Ps 47 is read seven times before the blowing of the shofar on Rosh Hashanah (the Jewish New Year), celebrating YHWH's enthronement as cosmic king. 'Clap your hands, all you peoples; shout to God with a joyful cry' — the hand-clapping (<em>tiq'u kaf</em>) and shouting (<em>teruah</em>) were the formal acclamations performed at a king's coronation in the ancient Near East. All peoples (<em>kol-ha'amim</em>) — not just Israel — are summoned to perform this royal acclamation.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'For the LORD Most High is to be feared; he is a great King over the whole earth' — 'LORD Most High' (<em>Yhwh Elyon</em>) — combining YHWH's covenant name with the Canaanite title <em>El Elyon</em> (God Most High, the supreme deity of the Canaanite pantheon; cf. Gen 14:18-20: Melchizedek priest of <em>El Elyon</em>; Deut 32:8: <em>El Elyon</em> dividing the nations). The Psalm appropriates the supreme Canaanite divine title and applies it to YHWH: YHWH is not one deity among many but the supreme king over the entire earth. 'Great King over the whole earth' (<em>melech gadol al-kol-ha'arets</em>) — the universal scope that the psalm will elaborate in vv. 7-9.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'He subdues peoples under us and nations beneath our feet' — the covenant warfare of YHWH on Israel's behalf: YHWH as the divine warrior who gives his client-people victory over nations. 'Under us' (<em>tachtenu</em>) and 'beneath our feet' (<em>tachat raglenu</em>) are the postures of the defeated enemy in the ancient Near East — the image of the king standing on the necks of prostrate enemies was a standard motif in Egyptian and Mesopotamian royal iconography. The footstool image of Ps 110:1 ('until I make your enemies your footstool') uses the same imagery.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'He chose our inheritance for us, the glory of Jacob whom he loved. Selah' — YHWH's choice (<em>yivchar</em>) of Israel's inheritance (<em>nachalatenu</em>, our inheritance/portion = the land of Canaan and the covenant relationship) is the foundation of all the military and political celebration. Behind the nations' subjection and Israel's ascendancy lies not military prowess but divine election and love. 'The glory of Jacob' (<em>ge'on ya'aqov</em>, the pride/majesty of Jacob) is the land or the status that YHWH gives to the covenant people. Selah again marks the liturgical pause for the congregation to receive this theological claim before the second strophe of praise (vv. 5-9).</p>",
    "5": "<p>'God has ascended with shouts of joy, the LORD with the sound of a ram's horn (<em>shofar</em>)' — the ascent (<em>alah Elohim</em>) is the key verse for the psalm's function as an enthronement song. The 'ascent' refers to YHWH ascending to his throne — probably enacted in liturgical procession where the ark (the throne of YHWH's presence) was carried to the sanctuary amid shouts of joy (<em>teruah</em>) and the shofar blast. The same event is narrated in 2 Sam 6:15 (ark brought to Jerusalem with 'shouting and the sound of trumpets'). The Psalm dramatizes YHWH's royal ascent to the heavenly court.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Sing praises to God, sing praises! Sing praises to our King, sing praises!' — the fourfold call to praise (<em>zammeru Elohim zammeru</em>) is a liturgical intensification: the same word repeated four times in four successive half-verses. <em>Zamar</em> (sing praises, make music) is the term for the musical praise of the temple liturgy (Ps 9:2; 21:13; 30:4; 57:7-9; 68:4, 32). The repetition creates the effect of cumulative acclamation — a liturgical crescendo of communal praise. 'Our King' (<em>malchenu</em>) moves from the cosmic scope ('God') to the covenant relationship ('our').</p>",
    "7": "<p>'For God is the King of the whole earth; sing praises with understanding (<em>maskil</em>)' — '<em>maskil</em>' here (usually a term in psalm superscriptions) appears in the body of the psalm, meaning 'with wisdom/discernment' — worship that understands what it is doing and why. The 'whole earth' (<em>kol-ha'arets</em>) as YHWH's kingdom: not merely Israel, not merely the ancient Near East, but the entire inhabited world. The commanded wisdom in praising ensures that the worship is not mere emotional enthusiasm but intelligent acknowledgment of what is true about YHWH's sovereignty.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'God reigns over the nations; God is seated on his holy throne' — the present-tense declaration: YHWH reigns (<em>malach Elohim al-goyim</em>) now, actively, over nations. The 'holy throne' (<em>kissei qodsho</em>) is both the ark of the covenant as the earthly throne and the cosmic throne above the heavens (Isa 6:1: 'I saw the Lord seated on a high and lofty throne'). The enthronement is not merely anticipated (future) but affirmed (present): YHWH's kingship over the nations is a current reality, not only an eschatological hope.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'The nobles of the nations have gathered as the people of the God of Abraham; for the rulers of the earth belong to God; he is greatly exalted' — the eschatological ingathering: the 'nobles' (<em>nedivim</em>) or princes of the nations are gathered as the people of the God of Abraham. This is the fulfillment of the Abrahamic promise (Gen 12:3: 'all peoples of the earth shall be blessed through you'): the nations' leaders join the covenant community of YHWH's people. 'For the rulers of the earth belong to God' (<em>ki le-Elohim maginei-arets</em>, for the shields of the earth belong to God) — all national power and authority is ultimately subject to the divine king. The psalm closes with the maximum scope: YHWH greatly exalted above all earthly sovereignty.</p>"
  },
  "110": {
    "1": "<p>Psalm 110 is the most frequently quoted OT text in the NT. Jesus cites it in the Synoptics (Matt 22:41-46 and parallels) as a riddle about the Messiah's nature. Peter cites it at Pentecost (Acts 2:34-35). Paul cites it (1 Cor 15:25; Eph 1:20; Col 3:1). Hebrews cites or alludes to it eight times (1:3, 13; 5:6, 10; 6:20; 7:17, 21; 8:1; 10:12-13). Its dominance in NT Christology is due to its dual claim: (1) divine enthronement at God's right hand; (2) eternal Melchizedekian priesthood. These two — divine lordship and perfect priesthood — are the two Christological pillars the NT builds on from this one Psalm.</p>"
  }
}

PSA_CHRIST = {
  "2": {
    "7": "<p>A direct revelation: 'You are my Son; today I have begotten you.' The royal Psalm 2 reaches its Christological fullness in the resurrection. Paul at Pisidian Antioch (Acts 13:33): God raised Jesus, 'as it is written in the second Psalm, You are my Son, today I have begotten you.' The 'today' of divine fatherhood is not the eternal generation alone but the specific day of the resurrection-enthronement, when the Son's identity is publicly declared. Every application of Ps 2:7 in the NT (baptism, transfiguration, resurrection) marks a moment when the Father publicly declares the Son's identity for the community to hear.</p>"
  },
  "22": {
    "1": "<p>A fulfillment: 'My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?' The Passion Psalm that Jesus cited from the cross is both a historical lament (David in extremity) and a Christological prophecy (the Son's abandonment in the atonement). The cry 'why have you forsaken me' is not a failure of faith but a genuine experience of divine absence — the moment when Christ bore the full weight of human sin-under-judgment. The Psalm's movement (dereliction → trust → vindication → universal proclamation) is the death-and-resurrection narrative in miniature. Jesus did not die in despair; the Psalm he cited ends in the world's worship of YHWH through the one who suffered.</p>"
  },
  "110": {
    "1": "<p>A direct revelation: 'The LORD says to my Lord: Sit at my right hand until I make your enemies your footstool.' The most foundational Christological oracle in the OT: the risen and ascended Christ is enthroned at the Father's right hand (the supreme position of divine authority) awaiting the final subjection of all enemies, including death (1 Cor 15:25-26). The present era is the era of Christ's enthronement: he reigns now, his enemies are being progressively placed under his feet, and the ultimate subjection is certain. Ps 110:1 frames the entire NT's understanding of the ascension and the present Christological situation of the cosmos.</p>",

    "4": "<p>A fulfillment: 'You are a priest forever after the order of Melchizedek.' The divine oath of the eternal priesthood is fulfilled in Christ's resurrection, which established him as the priest who never dies. Unlike the Levitical priests who needed to offer sacrifice repeatedly and who were replaced by death, Christ offered himself once and lives forever in the power of an indestructible life (Heb 7:16, 24-25). The Melchizedekian priesthood — prior to Aaron, not from the tribe of Levi, without recorded end — is the OT's own signal that the Levitical system was provisional. Christ's eternal intercession ('he always lives to make intercession for them', Heb 7:25) is the fulfillment of Ps 110:4's oath.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    e = load_echo('psalms')
    merge_echo(e, PSA_ECHO)
    save_echo('psalms', e)
    print(f'Psalms echo: {len(e)} chapters, {sum(len(v) for v in e.values())} verses')

    c = load_comm('mkt-original', 'psalms')
    merge_comm(c, PSA_ORIGINAL)
    save_comm('mkt-original', 'psalms', c)
    print(f'Psalms original: {len(c)} chapters, {sum(len(v) for v in c.values())} verses')

    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'psalms')
    merge_comm(c, PSA_CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'psalms', c)
    print(f'Psalms context: {len(c)} chapters, {sum(len(v) for v in c.values())} verses')

    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'psalms')
    merge_comm(c, PSA_CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'psalms', c)
    print(f'Psalms christ: {len(c)} chapters, {sum(len(v) for v in c.values())} verses')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
